The paper proposes a Bayesian formulation for multiple kernel learning, which is a common topic in machine learning and falls under the category of "Learning" (cs.LG). The paper also mentions experiments on bioinformatics and image recognition data sets, which are common application areas for artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computer vision (cs.CV), and natural language processing (cs.CL). Finally, the paper discusses how the proposed method can be extended for semi-supervised learning, which is a topic in "Social and Information Networks" (cs.SI).
